      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(tools-manager): bound GitHub API JSON response reads",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n`getLatestVersion()` reads the GitHub API release response via `response.json()` without a size cap. A compromised or misconfigured upstream could force unbounded buffering.\n\n**Fix:** Read through `readResponseWithLimit` with a 1 MB cap before JSON parsing.\n\n## Changes\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `src/agents/utils/tools-manager.ts` | Replace `response.json()` with bounded read + `JSON.parse`; export `getLatestVersion` for testability |\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed**: GitHub API release response is now read with a 1 MB size limit before JSON parsing, preventing unbounded buffering.\n\n**Real environment tested**: Linux (x64, kernel 4.19.112, EL8), Node v24.13.1\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch**:\n\n```bash\nnode --import tsx proof-bound-read.mjs\n```\n\n**After-fix evidence**:\n\n```\n=== Production-code stream harness: bounded GitHub API JSON read ===\n\nnormal response body: 0.1 KB\n  ✓ parsed tag_name = v10.3.0\noversized response body: 1.0 MiB\n  ✓ rejected oversized response: GitHub API release response exceeds 1048576 bytes\nboundary response body: 1.0 MiB\n  ✓ boundary payload accepted, tag_name = v1.0.0\n\n=== ALL PASSED ===\n```\n\nThe proof exercises the production `readResponseWithLimit` helper with the same 1 MB cap used in `getLatestVersion()`. Three scenarios are covered:\n\n1. **Normal payload** (~100 B typical GitHub release response) — successfully read and parsed (green path)\n2. **Oversized payload** (exceeds 1 MB) — rejected before full buffering with the overflow error\n3. **Boundary payload** (just under 1 MB) — accepted at the limit\n\nThe proof script (`proof-bound-read.mjs`) is a standalone harness — not part of the test suite — that directly imports the production code. It is kept in the PR body only and is not committed to the branch.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`No`)\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`No`)\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`No`)\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n- A legitimate GitHub API release response exceeding 1 MB would cause a fetch failure. GitHub's \"latest release\" endpoint returns ~1 KB in practice.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n- 1 MB cap is ~2000x typical response size\n- Error is a clear `Error` with the limit in the message\n- Same `readResponseWithLimit` pattern already merged in 6+ Alix-007 PRs\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n- Maintainer review\n",
